<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="111" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,572,1194,1221]" box="[151,572,1194,1221]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
<taxonomicName authority="De Geer, 1773" authorityName="De Geer" authorityYear="1773" box="[151,572,1194,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Gryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bimaculatus">
<emphasis box="[151,390,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Gryllus bimaculatus</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[397,572,1194,1221]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">De Geer, 1773</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1267,1365]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
Quite common within the rural-urban fringe and in synanthropic environments. A recent case of accidental introduction is reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Massa, B. &amp; Fontana, P." box="[363,645,1303,1329]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" pagination="405 - 434" refId="ref8204" refString="Massa, B. &amp; Fontana, P. (2020) Endemism in Italian Orthoptera. Biodiversity Journal, 11 (2), 405 - 434. https: // doi. org / 10.31396 / Biodiv. Jour. 2020.11.2.405.434" type="journal article" year="2020">
Massa &amp; 
<collectingRegion box="[470,560,1303,1329]" country="Malta" name="Fontana" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Fontana</collectingRegion>
(2020)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="113" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1267,1365]" box="[199,1306,1338,1365]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1338,1364]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Distribution</emphasis>
. Fairly extensive range comprising the Palaearctic, Oriental and Afrotropical regions.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,570,1446,1473]" box="[151,570,1446,1473]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus, 1758" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[151,570,1446,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Gryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="campestris">
<emphasis box="[151,374,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Gryllus campestris</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[381,570,1446,1472]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Linnaeus, 1758</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1518,1653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
A very uncommon species, known solely from a handful of sparse recorded occurrences (
<bibRefCitation author="Lanfranco, G." box="[1165,1349,1518,1545]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" pagination="271 - 272" refId="ref8018" refString="Lanfranco, G. (1955) Orthoptera of the Maltese Islands: remarks and additions. Entomologist, 88, 271 - 272." type="journal article" year="1955">Lanfranco 1955</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cassar, L. F." pageId="4" pageNumber="111" pagination="1 - 4" refId="ref7185" refString="Cassar, L. F. (1990 a) Notes on rare and infrequent Orthoptera of the Maltese Islands. Central Mediterranean Naturalist, 2 (1), 1 - 4." type="journal article" year="1990">Cassar 1990a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1518,1653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1590,1616]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Distribution</emphasis>
. Western Palaearctic region; however, markedly less common than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Geer" authorityYear="1773" box="[1096,1266,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Gryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bimaculatus">
<emphasis box="[1096,1266,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">G. bimaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the southern part of the region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,696,1734,1761]" box="[151,696,1734,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
<taxonomicName authority="(Lefebvre, 1827)" baseAuthorityName="Lefebvre" baseAuthorityYear="1827" box="[151,696,1734,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Brachytrupes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megacephalus">
<emphasis box="[151,485,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Brachytrupes megacephalus</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[492,696,1734,1760]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">(Lefebvre, 1827)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1807,2013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">
A vulnerable, stenotopic species known from both 
<collectingCountry box="[719,784,1807,1833]" name="Malta" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Malta</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[838,901,1807,1833]" country="Malta" name="Zebbug" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Gozo</collectingRegion>
, where it maintains relatively small populations in coastal localities, mostly on sandy habitats but also on Quaternary substrates (
<bibRefCitation author="Cassar, L. F. &amp; Conrad E." box="[1037,1296,1843,1869]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" pagination="59 - 62" refId="ref7379" refString="Cassar, L. F. &amp; Conrad E. (2008) New populations of Brachytrupes megacephalus (Lefevre, 1827) on mainland Malta and some notes on its adaptive capacity (Orthoptera: Gryllidae). Bulletin of the Entomological Society of Malta, 1, 59 - 62." type="journal article" year="2008">Cassar &amp; Conrad 2008</bibRefCitation>
). The largest population occurs at Ghadira, on the main island, within less than two kilometres from the Ahrax promontory, where a metapopulation made up of at least eleven subpopulation clusters has been recorded (
<bibRefCitation author="Cassar, L. F. &amp; Galdies, C. &amp; Xuereb, N." box="[1112,1316,1915,1941]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" pagination="21 - 28" refId="ref7484" refString="Cassar, L. F., Galdies, C. &amp; Xuereb, N. (2018) An evaluation of risk from sea-level rise and storm surge on sub-populations of Brachytrupes megacephalus (Lefebvre, 1827) (Orthoptera Gryllidae) on the island of Malta. Bulletin of the Entomological Society of Malta, 10, 21 - 28." type="journal article" year="2018">
Cassar 
<emphasis box="[1195,1243,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">et al</emphasis>
. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
). Only one population is known from 
<collectingRegion box="[452,515,1951,1977]" country="Malta" name="Zebbug" pageId="4" pageNumber="111">Gozo</collectingRegion>
, which occurs within the sand dunes and adjacent agricultural land at Ramla Bay on the northern coast of the island (
<bibRefCitation author="Cassar, L. F." box="[547,691,1987,2013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="111" pagination="274 - 275" refId="ref7306" refString="Cassar, L. F. (2019) Of naturalists and crickets: How an off-chance discovery led to a lifelong journey of scientific inquiry. In: Falzon, M. - A. (Ed.), T he Examined Life: Writings in of honour of Guido Lanfranco. Midsea Books Limited, Valletta, pp. 97 - 111, 6 figs. 274 - 275." type="journal article" year="2019">Cassar 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,150,321]" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,150,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">Distribution</emphasis>
. Mediterranean, specifically parts of North Africa, the central Mediterranean area and southern tip of 
<collectingRegion box="[219,316,187,213]" country="Italy" name="Sardegna" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">Sardinia</collectingRegion>
. It also occurs in the central Sahara, on the northern fringe of the Afrotropical region. In Europe, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lefebvre" baseAuthorityYear="1827" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Brachytrupes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megacephalus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">B. megacephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only occurs within Italian (
<collectingRegion box="[614,681,223,249]" country="Italy" name="Sicilia" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">Sicily</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[732,827,223,250]" country="Italy" name="Sardegna" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">Sardinia</collectingRegion>
) and Maltese territories, where it is afforded protection via a number of Natura 2000 sites. The species has also been afforded protection status through the EU Habitats Directive (92/43/EEC) and the Bern Convention (
<bibRefCitation author="Cassar, L. F. &amp; Galdies, C. &amp; Xuereb, N." box="[708,915,295,321]" pageId="5" pageNumber="112" pagination="127" refId="ref7432" refString="Cassar, L. F., Galdies, C. &amp; Xuereb, N. (2017) Evaluating risks from sea-level rise on metapopulations of Brachytrupes megacephalus (Lefebvre, 1827) on the island of Malta. Bulletin of the Entomological Society of Malta, 9, 127." type="journal article" year="2017">
Cassar 
<emphasis box="[791,840,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
